column884: there is already a mistake/typo in the question: 1Sv = 1mio m3/s, the 1 mio can be expresses as 1e6, 10^6 or so but not 106. The first answer made a calculation mistake in calculating the vol of basin, which is 16.8 x 1e15 and not 16.8 x 1e9. The further answers then continue calculating with this mistake but in a way correctly, because the candidate used the definition as given in the question. So the result is then wrong, once because the candidate made one calculation mistake and second because the candidate used a wrong definition. The second answer was completely correct, only the conversion of seconds to year could have been more complete (there was only a number of seconds/year given without providing insights into how that was calculated). It was also good that the candidate said that this answer is valid when only considering the inflow from the Bering straight and the rivers, but disregarding other sources (landrunof which might be high in a global warming scenario, pot inflow from the atlantic). Answer 3 had several mistakes: the volume calculation was missing an indication for exponent 16.8 x 1015 16.8 x 10^15. This was however minor, because the candidate calcualates then with 16.8 x 10^15, but makes a mistake by converting 14e6 sec to days.
